.  aThe gigantic explosion that laid waste to large parts of the Siberian Tunguska region on 30 June 1908 is one of the most devastating natural disasters of the 20th century. It's destructive power, however, cannot be expressed in numbers. Rather, the catastrophic potential of the Tunguska event lies more in its persistent mysteriousness. The lack of a cogent explanation shakes the modern production of knowledge to its very foundations. Solvejg Nitzke's analysis of the Tunguska discourse, which comprises academic, para-academic, and literary texts, does not just reveal the limits of the central conceptions of the modern era, but also opens up new possibilities for cultural studies research.  afunded by VG-Wort (7557-2016)  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aCatastrophical, The. 0aDisasters in literature. 0aDiscourse analysis. 0aSciencexSocial aspectsxHistoryy20th century. 0aScientific literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aTunguska meteoritexResearchxHistory. 4aAllgemeine Literaturwissenschaft. 4aExplosion. 4aKatastrophe. 4aKultur. 4aKulturtheorie. 4aKulturwissenschaft. 4aLiteratur. 4aLiteraturwissenschaft. 4aModerne. 4aPopkultur. 4aRätsel. 4aScience Fiction. 4aSibirien. 4aTunguska-Ereignis. 4aTunguska. 4aVerschwörungstheorie. 4aWissensproduktion. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aCatastrophe.  aConspiracy Theory.  aCultural Studies.  aCultural Theory.  aCulture.  aExplosion.  aGeneral Literature Studies.  aKnowledge Production.  aLiterary Studies.  aLiterature.  aModernity.  aMystery.  aPopular Culture.  aScience Fiction.  aSiberia.  aTunguska Event.  aTunguska.2 aVG-Wort (7557-2016)efunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2017z97831107195